<gmd:abstract>             <gco:CharacterString>Baseline (1961-1990) average air temperature (degree C) for Alaska and Western Canada. Baseline results for 1961-1990 are derived from Climate Research Unit (CRU) TS 3.1 data. Data courtesy of Scenarios Network for Alaska and Arctic Planning. The file names identifies whether a file represents an annual (i.e., annual) mean or a seasonal mean (i.e., summer or winter). Summer is defined as June - August; winter is defined as December - February.</gco:CharacterString>          </gmd:abstract>          <gmd:purpose>             <gco:CharacterString>This raster was created to depict 'baseline' conditions for climate maps created by Arctic Landscape Conservation Cooperative staff. For the purpose of these data, baseline is the period between 1961 and 1990.</gco:CharacterString>          </gmd:purpose>          <gmd:credit>             <gco:CharacterString>Created by Arctic <gmd:description>                         <gco:CharacterString>Data originates from the Climatic Research Unit (CRU, http://www.cru.uea.ac.uk/) TS 3.1.01 dataset that was downscaled to 2km by SNAP. These files are bias corrected and downscaled via the delta method using PRISM (http://prism.oregonstate.edu/) 1961-1990 (for 2km Alaska and Western Canada data). Questions about the CRU dataset should be addressed to SNAP. Climate data downloaded from the SNAP website (http://www.snap.uaf.edu/downloads/alaska-climate-datasets) and subsequently processed by Arctic LCC staff using ArcGIS 10.0 and 10.1 software. Arctic LCC staff used the downscaled data to calculate baseline average air temperature.</gco:CharacterString>                      </gmd:description>                      <gmd:dateTime>
